snippet.textDisplay:
Dumping fuel is not uncommon in emergencies for jets... but my question is why it dumped there rather than in a prescribed fuel dump area.

I mean, come on... it’s a compressor stall on one engine. There is absolutely no reason that they could not have diverted to a fuel dump area... plus they specifically told ATC that they didn’t need to dump.

Also, being aerosolized, it is highly flammable.

snippet.textDisplay: Those people who had jet fuel dumped on them may be physically "fine", but they are far from fine .. the first many lawsuits were filed on Friday against the pilot of that plane and the airline company he works for. The pilot was asked by the tower, repeatedly, if they needed to circle and dump fuel(at a safe height). The pilot repeatedly refused. It wasn't until approach that the pilot decided to dump his fuel load(under the FAA safe height), without notifying the tower.
snippet.textOriginal: Those people who had jet fuel dumped on them may be physically "fine", but they are far from *fine* .. the first many lawsuits were filed on Friday against the pilot of that plane *and* the airline company he works for. The pilot was asked by the tower, repeatedly, if they needed to circle and dump fuel(at a safe height). The pilot repeatedly refused. It wasn't until approach that the pilot decided to dump his fuel load(under the FAA safe height), without notifying the tower.
